1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074


2
00:01:31,920 --> 00:01:35,310
<i>This story consists of my recollections</i>
<i>of a very unusual young man... </i>

3
00:01:35,480 --> 00:01:38,552
<i>... with whom I was thrown</i>
<i>into contact at long intervals. </i>

4
00:01:38,720 --> 00:01:40,756
<i>In the summer of 1919... </i>

5
00:01:40,920 --> 00:01:43,878
. <i>... while passing through Chicago</i>
<i>on my way to the Far East... </i>

6
00:01:44,040 --> 00:01:46,235
<i>... a friend of mine, Elliott Templeton... </i>

7
00:01:46,400 --> 00:01:48,436
<i>... whom I had known</i>
<i>in London and Paris... </i>

8
00:01:48,600 --> 00:01:52,070
<i>... invited me to dine with him</i>
<i>and his sister, Mrs. Bradley. </i>

9
00:01:52,240 --> 00:01:55,630
<i>They were giving a dinner party at</i>
<i>one of those sprawling country clubs... </i>

10
00:01:55,800 --> 00:01:58,189
<i>... which were so much a part</i>
<i>of the American scene... </i>

11
00:01:58,360 --> 00:02:00,510
<i>... in the early days</i>
<i>of the postwar boom. </i>

12
00:02:20,880 --> 00:02:23,474
- Good evening, sir.
- Good evening. Mr. Templeton's table.

13
00:02:23,640 --> 00:02:25,517
- Yes, sir.
- Are they here?

14
00:02:25,680 --> 00:02:28,069
They're having refreshments, sir.

15
00:02:44,800 --> 00:02:47,189
- Oh, here you are.
- With a dry martini, sir.

16
00:02:47,360 --> 00:02:49,510
Prohibition, of all the bloody nonsense.

17
00:02:49,680 --> 00:02:51,159
- Elliott.
- Yes, dear?

18
00:02:51,320 --> 00:02:53,151
Who is this man
that you asked to dinner?

19
00:02:53,320 --> 00:02:55,880
I had to get Sophie last minute
or we woulďve been 13.

20
00:02:56,040 --> 00:02:59,828
He's an English author. He's quite
all right. In fact, he's really quite famous.

21
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:01,911
So pretend that you've heard of him.

22
00:03:02,080 --> 00:03:04,275
That's too much. Get the other glasses.

23
00:03:04,440 --> 00:03:07,557
Elliott, you must be slipping
if you frequent authors.

24
00:03:07,720 --> 00:03:10,871
Not at all, my dear.
Authors go everywhere nowadays.

25
00:03:11,040 --> 00:03:14,589
Why, in London, I even met actors
and actresses in society.

26
00:03:14,920 --> 00:03:16,956
Here he is now.

27
00:03:18,200 --> 00:03:20,555
My dear fellow,
how very nice to see you.

28
00:03:20,720 --> 00:03:21,789
Hello, Elliott.

29
00:03:21,960 --> 00:03:24,838
Let me present you to my sister,
Mrs. Bradley.

30
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:26,592
Louisa.

31
00:03:27,360 --> 00:03:31,273
Louisa, dear,
this is Mr. Somerset Maugham.

32
00:03:31,440 --> 00:03:34,352
How do you do, Mr. Maugham?
It's an honor to have you with us.

33
00:03:34,520 --> 00:03:36,238
Thank you. It's very nice to be here.

34
00:03:36,400 --> 00:03:38,709
What on earth are you doing
in this benighted city?

35
00:03:38,880 --> 00:03:42,111
I'm just passing through, but you,
I thought you never left Paris.

36
00:03:42,280 --> 00:03:43,508
Why should I?

37
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:46,319
In fact, I came to see my sister
and my niece, Isabel.

38
00:03:46,480 --> 00:03:49,278
I haven't been back
since before the war.

39
00:03:49,760 --> 00:03:52,957
I hope you don't mind, a few
young things are joining us for dinner...

40
00:03:53,120 --> 00:03:54,599
...but we can leave early.

41
00:03:54,760 --> 00:03:58,070
Why should I mind? I like young things
if they're good to look at.

42
00:03:58,240 --> 00:04:02,358
Incidentally, you'll meet the young man
my niece has got herself engaged to.

43
00:04:02,520 --> 00:04:06,229
His name is Larry Darrell, and I'll tell you
that Elliott doesn't approve of him.

44
00:04:06,400 --> 00:04:10,188
I have nothing against him, but he hasn't
any money. And my sister's not rich.

45
00:04:10,360 --> 00:04:12,316
- She needs all she's got.
- Elliott...

46
00:04:12,480 --> 00:04:15,358
...is it necessary to tell Mr. Maugham
all our private affairs?

47
00:04:15,520 --> 00:04:18,671
- We can't all be millionaires, Elliott.
- He hasn't even got a job.

48
00:04:18,840 --> 00:04:20,956
- He can get one.
- He doesn't want a job.

49
00:04:21,120 --> 00:04:23,839
- Why not?
- Because he's bone idle.

50
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:27,549
That must shock a man like you
who's never earned a penny in his life.

51
00:04:28,280 --> 00:04:30,555
It may have escaped your notice,
my dear fellow...

52
00:04:30,720 --> 00:04:32,836
...but I am not an ordinary man.

53
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:35,118
- Cocktail?
- Oh, yes, please.

54
00:04:35,280 --> 00:04:37,475
For the run of mankind,
industry is essential.

55
00:04:37,640 --> 00:04:40,757
I see no reason why this man
my niece has got herself engaged to...

56
00:04:40,920 --> 00:04:44,196
...should not conform
to the customs of his country.

57
00:04:45,280 --> 00:04:46,838
Here's my niece now.

58
00:04:53,680 --> 00:04:55,352
Oh, Mother.

59
00:04:56,840 --> 00:04:58,068
- Hello, Isabel.
- Hello.

60
00:04:58,240 --> 00:05:01,038
- This is my daughter, Isabel.
- How do you do, Mr. Maugham?

61
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:03,270
- Where's Larry?
- Late.

62
00:05:03,440 --> 00:05:07,035
Poor sweet. I suppose he forgot
to wind his watch last night as usual.

63
00:05:07,200 --> 00:05:08,952
You wouldn't know about Larry.

64
00:05:09,120 --> 00:05:10,997
Say, Mother, you've mixed up
the cards...

65
00:05:11,160 --> 00:05:12,673
- Oh, Sophie, dear.
- Hello, Sophie.

66
00:05:12,840 --> 00:05:16,276
This is Sophie Nelson. Sophie
is a neighbor of ours in the country.

67
00:05:16,440 --> 00:05:18,351
- How do you do?
- You look charming, Sophie.

68
00:05:18,520 --> 00:05:20,636
Yes, doesn't she? Excuse us.

69
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:23,758
Come here.
I want to have a look at you.

70
00:05:23,920 --> 00:05:27,469
- Sophie, you look lovely.
- It's the dress.

71
00:05:27,640 --> 00:05:30,279
- You sure you don't mind my wearing it?
- Of course not.

72
00:05:30,440 --> 00:05:33,750
- Lf you like it, take it as a present.
- Oh, that's awfully sweet of you.

73
00:05:33,920 --> 00:05:36,878
Oh, it'll be such a surprise for Bob
to see me decently dressed.

74
00:05:37,040 --> 00:05:40,430
Oh, you know Bob's much too much in
love with you to notice what you wear.

75
00:05:40,600 --> 00:05:43,876
He's no more crazy about me
than I am about him.

76
00:05:44,040 --> 00:05:47,715
I don't think anyone ever loved
anyone as I love him.

77
00:05:47,880 --> 00:05:50,440
- Isn't it heavenly to be alive?
- Yes.

78
00:05:50,600 --> 00:05:51,919
- Hi.
- Hello, Gray.

79
00:05:52,080 --> 00:05:53,718
- Hello, Gray.
- May I break this up?

80
00:05:53,880 --> 00:05:55,108
Sure.

81
00:05:55,280 --> 00:05:56,759
Hello.

82
00:05:57,400 --> 00:05:59,868
- You look lovely.
- Think so?

83
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:03,477
- Hello, Sophie.
- Hello.

84
00:06:03,640 --> 00:06:05,278
May I get you one, Miss...?

85
00:06:05,440 --> 00:06:07,431
- Miss Nelson, isn't it?
- Yes, Sophie Nelson.

86
00:06:07,600 --> 00:06:09,113
I'd love it.

87
00:06:09,280 --> 00:06:10,998
No, I guess I'd better not.

88
00:06:11,160 --> 00:06:13,628
- Why? What's wrong with cocktails?
- Oh, nothing.

89
00:06:13,800 --> 00:06:16,075
Only, I promised Bob I wouldn't.

90
00:06:16,240 --> 00:06:18,390
- Who's Bob?
- My boyfriend.

91
00:06:18,560 --> 00:06:21,757
He doesn't like me to drink.
He thinks I'm too fond of it.

92
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:24,912
- Which is Bob?
- Oh, he isn't here. He's working.

93
00:06:25,080 --> 00:06:27,230
He's putting himself
through law school.

94
00:06:27,400 --> 00:06:29,311
He's gonna drop in later
and take me home.

95
00:06:29,480 --> 00:06:32,392
Will you have one of these?
If my man Joseph could see me now...

96
00:06:32,560 --> 00:06:35,518
...I give you my word,
he'd faint dead away.

97
00:06:36,640 --> 00:06:38,471
You're a great friend
of Mr. Templeton's.

98
00:06:38,640 --> 00:06:42,553
Oh, I wouldn't say that. Elliott has
no friends, only acquaintances.

99
00:06:42,840 --> 00:06:46,355
- He's an awful snob, isn't he?
- Oh, awful. But he's kind and generous.

100
00:06:46,520 --> 00:06:49,478
People laugh at him, but they eat
his food and drink his wine.

101
00:06:49,680 --> 00:06:52,513
Oh, Mr. Maugham. Mr. Maugham,
you're next to Mother.

102
00:06:52,680 --> 00:06:54,511
And Sophie, you're next to Gray.

103
00:06:54,680 --> 00:06:57,114
- That's us, toots.
- Mr. Maugham, Mr. Maturin.

104
00:06:57,280 --> 00:06:58,508
- Isabel.
- Yes?

105
00:06:58,680 --> 00:07:01,353
- Dinner, my dear fellow.
- Oh, yes.

106
00:07:02,680 --> 00:07:04,830
And who's Mr. Maturin?

107
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:07,389
Oh, Gray. He's our millionaire.

108
00:07:07,560 --> 00:07:09,630
His father's a big broker.
We're proud of him.

109
00:07:09,800 --> 00:07:12,519
He gives us class. But he's nice.

110
00:07:12,680 --> 00:07:15,877
I know several girls who'd stop
at nothing short of murder to get him.

111
00:07:16,040 --> 00:07:18,156
- They haven't a chance.
- Why not?

112
00:07:18,320 --> 00:07:20,595
He's so in love with Isabel
he can't see straight.

113
00:07:20,760 --> 00:07:24,070
I see. And she's in love
with Larry Darrell.

114
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:25,992
I suppose that does
complicate matters.

115
00:07:26,160 --> 00:07:29,391
It does, if you're as
high-principled as Gray is.

116
00:07:29,560 --> 00:07:31,551
And Larry isn't here.

117
00:07:39,960 --> 00:07:42,269
Yes, he's just coming in now,
way over there. Look.

118
00:07:42,440 --> 00:07:44,476
Come on, dinner.

119
00:07:55,960 --> 00:07:58,554
<i>This is the young man</i>
<i>of whom I write. </i>

120
00:07:58,720 --> 00:08:00,392
<i>He is not famous. </i>

121
00:08:00,560 --> 00:08:03,552
<i>It may be that when his life</i>
<i>at last comes to an end... </i>

122
00:08:03,720 --> 00:08:06,951
<i>... he will leave no more trace</i>
<i>of his sojourn on this earth... </i>

123
00:08:07,120 --> 00:08:11,477
<i>... than a stone thrown into a river</i>
<i>leaves on the surface of the water. </i>

124
00:08:11,640 --> 00:08:15,110
<i>Yet it may be that the way of life</i>
<i>he has chosen for himself... </i>

125
00:08:15,280 --> 00:08:18,875
<i>... may have an ever-growing influence</i>
<i>over his fellow men... </i>

126
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:21,156
<i>... so that, </i>
<i>long after his death perhaps... </i>

127
00:08:21,320 --> 00:08:27,190
<i>... it may be realized that there lived</i>
<i>in this age a very remarkable creature. </i>

128
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:29,911
- You're very late, Larry.
- I'm sorry.

129
00:08:30,080 --> 00:08:31,718
Sophie, where is Mr. Maugham?

130
00:08:31,880 --> 00:08:35,031
Larry hasn't learned that punctuality
is the politeness of kings.

131
00:08:35,200 --> 00:08:37,589
Elliott. Mr. Maugham,
this is Larry Darrell.

132
00:08:37,760 --> 00:08:41,275
- When can we start dinner?
- Mr. Maugham's a novelist, darling.

133
00:08:41,440 --> 00:08:44,432
I may as well tell you that Larry's
very stupid and uneducated.

134
00:08:44,600 --> 00:08:47,239
He knows nothing
about anything except flying.

135
00:08:47,400 --> 00:08:49,960
When he came back,
he looked so lovely in his uniform...

136
00:08:50,120 --> 00:08:52,918
...I camped on his doorstep
until he consented to marry me.

137
00:08:53,080 --> 00:08:55,799
- The competition was awful.
- Don't believe a word she says.

138
00:08:55,960 --> 00:08:58,269
Isabel's not a bad girl,
but she's a terrible liar.

139
00:08:58,440 --> 00:09:00,158
- Dinner.
- Oh, yes.

140
00:09:00,320 --> 00:09:02,311
I've seen you before.

141
00:09:02,520 --> 00:09:03,953
Oh, when?

142
00:09:04,120 --> 00:09:06,839
I happened to have work to do,
and I went into the library.

143
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:08,319
I saw you there this morning.

144
00:09:08,480 --> 00:09:10,755
When I came back from lunch,
you were still there.

145
00:09:10,920 --> 00:09:13,229
- I forgot about lunch.
- I couldn't help admiring...

146
00:09:13,400 --> 00:09:14,879
...your power of concentration.

147
00:09:15,040 --> 00:09:16,951
- It was that kind of a book.
- My fellow...

148
00:09:17,120 --> 00:09:19,588
...you're at the end of the table
with my sister.

149
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:21,956
- Hello, Gray.
- Hi there.

150
00:09:22,120 --> 00:09:24,918
Say, Dad tells me you turned down
that job in the office.

151
00:09:25,080 --> 00:09:27,594
Oh, Larry, why have you done that?

152
00:09:27,760 --> 00:09:30,593
I thought it over, and I figured
I'd be a disappointment...

153
00:09:30,760 --> 00:09:33,877
...so I decided I'd better refuse.
- Sorry, old man.

154
00:09:34,040 --> 00:09:36,679
It would have been swell,
us working together.

155
00:10:01,160 --> 00:10:04,152
Hi. Looks as if tall, dark and legal
is standing you up tonight.

156
00:10:04,320 --> 00:10:06,595
I'd like to catch him trying it.

157
00:10:06,760 --> 00:10:09,320
- You're old friends?
- We grew up together.

158
00:10:09,480 --> 00:10:11,914
I used to play shortstop
on his baseball team.

159
00:10:12,080 --> 00:10:14,469
We used to think we could lick
any 10 kids our size.

160
00:10:14,640 --> 00:10:17,154
- And could you?
- We tried.

161
00:10:17,320 --> 00:10:20,278
Oh, here comes my young man now.

162
00:10:21,880 --> 00:10:25,156
- Well, here you are.
- Hello.

163
00:10:31,760 --> 00:10:34,035
This is Mr. Maugham. Bob MacDonald.

164
00:10:34,200 --> 00:10:35,519
- How do you do?
- How are you?

165
00:10:35,680 --> 00:10:38,114
He's the one who seems to think
he wants to marry me.

166
00:10:38,280 --> 00:10:40,669
I can't see why, but there it is.

167
00:10:40,840 --> 00:10:43,195
I just happen to be crazy
about the girl.

168
00:10:43,360 --> 00:10:46,079
I wouldn't like him to know,
but just between you and me...

169
00:10:46,240 --> 00:10:49,550
...I rather like him myself.
- Let's dance.

170
00:11:15,360 --> 00:11:17,669
- Hello, Isabel.
- Hello.

171
00:11:17,840 --> 00:11:21,594
Larry, why didn't you tell me that
Mr. Maturin had offered you a job?

172
00:11:21,760 --> 00:11:23,159
What?

173
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:29,955
Larry, why didn't you tell me that
Mr. Maturin had offered you a job?

174
00:11:30,920 --> 00:11:32,592
Answer me.

175
00:11:32,760 --> 00:11:34,512
Answer me.

176
00:11:35,040 --> 00:11:38,430
Well, I thought I'd better not until
I made up my mind one way or another.

177
00:11:38,600 --> 00:11:39,589
You mad?

178
00:11:39,760 --> 00:11:41,751
Darling, that's the horrible part
about you.

179
00:11:41,920 --> 00:11:44,957
However aggravating you are,
one can't really be angry with you.

180
00:11:45,120 --> 00:11:47,031
Oh, can't they?

181
00:11:50,400 --> 00:11:52,470
Did you see those looks
Elliott was giving me?

182
00:11:52,640 --> 00:11:54,551
Well, after all, Larry, a man must work.

183
00:11:54,720 --> 00:11:57,598
And the longer you put it off,
the harder it'll be.

184
00:11:57,760 --> 00:12:00,797
I've got a foolish notion I want
to do more than just sell bonds.

185
00:12:00,960 --> 00:12:02,791
All right, then.

186
00:12:03,720 --> 00:12:07,110
- Go into a law office.
- I don't wanna do that either.

187
00:12:08,480 --> 00:12:10,516
What do you want to do then?

188
00:12:12,760 --> 00:12:14,478
I don't know.

189
00:12:15,760 --> 00:12:17,034
Loaf, maybe.

190
00:12:18,440 --> 00:12:20,715
Oh, Larry, don't be funny.

191
00:12:20,880 --> 00:12:22,711
This is serious.

192
00:12:23,840 --> 00:12:26,513
I'm not being funny.
I think it's very serious.

193
00:12:38,400 --> 00:12:40,960
I wouldn't make you miserable
for anything.

194
00:12:41,120 --> 00:12:43,793
But you are making me miserable.

195
00:12:45,240 --> 00:12:47,196
You see, I love you.

196
00:12:47,360 --> 00:12:49,590
And I love you, Isabel.

197
00:13:02,080 --> 00:13:05,629
Look, Larry, let's be sensible.

198
00:13:05,840 --> 00:13:08,308
A man must work.
It's a matter of self-respect.

199
00:13:08,480 --> 00:13:12,189
This is a young country, and it's a
man's duty to take part in its activities.

200
00:13:12,360 --> 00:13:14,430
Gray's father was saying
only the other day...

201
00:13:14,600 --> 00:13:17,990
...that we're beginning an era that
will make the past look like 30 cents.

202
00:13:18,160 --> 00:13:20,469
He said that he can see
no limit to our progress...

203
00:13:20,640 --> 00:13:25,430
...and that by 1930, we'll be the greatest
and richest country in the whole world.

204
00:13:25,600 --> 00:13:28,717
- Don't you think that's terribly exciting?
- Terribly.

205
00:13:28,880 --> 00:13:31,235
Why, there never was such a chance
for a young man.

206
00:13:31,400 --> 00:13:33,709
I'd have thought
you'd be proud to be a part of it.

207
00:13:33,880 --> 00:13:37,793
- It's such a wonderful adventure.
- I'm sure you're right, Isabel.

208
00:13:37,960 --> 00:13:40,394
The Armours and Swifts
will pack more and better meat.

209
00:13:40,560 --> 00:13:42,596
The McCormicks will turn
out more harvesters.

210
00:13:42,760 --> 00:13:45,672
Henry Ford will make more cars,
and everybody will get richer.

211
00:13:45,840 --> 00:13:48,832
- And what's wrong with that?
- Nothing.

212
00:13:50,400 --> 00:13:52,960
Nothing. It just happens
that sitting in an office...

213
00:13:53,120 --> 00:13:55,350
...and making a lot of money
doesn't interest me.

214
00:13:55,560 --> 00:13:58,313
Oh, don't talk like a fool.
You can't live without money.

215
00:13:58,720 --> 00:14:01,553
I have a little. That's what gives me
the chance to do what I want.

216
00:14:01,720 --> 00:14:03,551
You're making it very difficult for me.

217
00:14:03,720 --> 00:14:06,473
I'm sorry, darling.
I wouldn't if I could help it.

218
00:14:09,680 --> 00:14:12,114
You can help it.

219
00:14:16,840 --> 00:14:18,432
Yes?

220
00:14:19,640 --> 00:14:22,837
The dead look so terribly dead
when they're dead.

221
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:26,913
- What does that mean, exactly?
- Just that.

222
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:30,355
Are you terribly unhappy, darling?

223
00:14:30,520 --> 00:14:34,274
No, the only thing that makes me
unhappy is making you unhappy.

224
00:14:34,880 --> 00:14:38,953
I don't think I'll ever find peace
until I make up my mind about things.

